text: BLOCKCHAIN FOR CARBON TRADING Author: - Digvijay Bangale, Pushpam Raj & Yashika Kumari Instructor: - Prof. Anil Vithalrao Turukmane  Abstract When we kicked off this project, our main thought was pretty simple: could blockchain actually make carbon trading better, or would it just be another flashy tech idea that sounds good on paper? We’d read about how credits get double counted, how deals take forever to verify, and how middlemen can swallow a big share of the money. It felt broken. We decided to try a different path — using ERC-20 tokens, smart contracts, and IoT devices so credits could be created, verified, and retired in a way that was transparent and quick. No unnecessary steps, no endless waiting. When we tested it, the difference was huge: settlement times dropped from days to minutes, costs went down to about 1–2%, and every step was visible to everyone involved. Honestly, it was satisfying to see something so simple make such a noticeable improvement.  Introduction One of the first things we talked about as a team was whether blockchain could solve real- world problems, not just sit there as a buzzword. Carbon markets have been around for a long time, but they aren’t smooth — you’ve got slow verification, high fees, and credits you can’t always trust. We wanted to build something that could work for both ends of the spectrum: a big company offsetting millions of tonnes and a small community planting trees by hand. The voluntary carbon market (VCM) is getting bigger every year — USD 4.04 billion in 2024, heading toward nearly USD 24 billion by 2030. That’s great, but if trust isn’t there, the growth could collapse in on itself. Our idea was to blend Ethereum-compatible smart contracts with real-time IoT monitoring. The blockchain side would handle the rules and transactions automatically, and the sensors would feed in live, verifiable environmental data. That’s how we aimed to plug the trust gap.  Background and Framework Carbon trading officially started with the Kyoto Protocol, then expanded through things like the EU Emissions Trading Scheme. The theory is good: measure emissions cuts, turn them into credits, trade them. But reality often means delays, paperwork, and costs that eat away at value. Some blockchain projects, like KlimaDAO and Toucan Protocol, have tried tokenizing credits already. They proved it was possible, but there were still cracks — like data reliability and the need to keep all participants engaged and honest. We went with the idea of “programmable environmental assets.” In our system, each token has embedded details about the project, the amount of CO₂ reduced, and the verification process. We broke the market into four main roles:  Consumers – buying credits (35%)  Generators – producing verified reductions (30%)  Validators – confirming authenticity (20%)  Regulators – overseeing compliance (15%) Blockchain Carbon Trading Stakeholders  System Design We structured the platform into four layers, mostly so it would be modular and easier to scale: 1. Blockchain Layer –

where tokens are created, traded, and eventually retired. 2. Application Layer – a Vue.js interface, so each type of user sees what’s relevant to them. 3. Integration Layer – connecting IoT sensors, satellite images, and registries. 4. User Layer – handling permissions and access control. When we compared it to the traditional process, the benefits were obvious: faster transactions, lower fees, no middlemen, real-time transparency, and the ability for anyone to take part from anywhere. Carbon Trading Comparison – Traditional vs Blockchain  Implementation and Results We set up the smart contracts on Hyperledger Fabric. It gave us over 1,000 transactions per second, credit issuance in around 2.3 seconds, and gas costs that were about 15–20% lower than a normal ERC-20 setup. It wasn’t all perfect. One rainy day, an IoT sensor went rogue and started sending odd CO₂ readings. The blockchain logged it without question, which reminded us — tech is only as good as the inputs. That’s why redundancy and validation layers are non-negotiable if this is going to work in the real world. Looking at where the carbon market is heading made us realise how big this could become. Carbon Market Growth Projections (2024–2030)  Feedback from Stakeholders We didn’t just want numbers — we wanted to hear from people. Most liked the transparency and the fact that once a credit was logged, it couldn’t be duplicated. Automated verification also made life easier by removing a lot of form-filling. Real-time monitoring gave buyers more confidence, which in turn could make the whole market more active. Key Benefits of Blockchain in Carbon Trading  Discussion One thing we learned quickly is that blockchain can improve speed and trust, but it’s not a magic wand. The real environmental value depends on accurate data, honest measurements, and solid governance. Without those, it’s just a fancy database. We also realised that cutting transaction costs could open the market to smaller projects. Before, many local or community-based initiatives couldn’t afford to join in. Now, they might be able to — and those smaller projects, when combined, could have a massive impact. There are still hurdles: smart contracts can be complex, rules vary by region, and there’s no universal standard for trading credits yet. But these are challenges we think can be solved with time and collaboration.  Conclusion We built something that worked in testing — it made trades faster, cheaper, and more transparent. But the takeaway isn’t that blockchain solves everything. It’s that, when combined with solid monitoring and good governance, it can be a real force for change. Next, we want to try it on live projects, strengthen our IoT setup so bad weather doesn’t throw it off, work with regulators to make sure everything is compliant, and explore ways for credits to move easily between platforms. If we can make that happen, the carbon market could become not just bigger, but better for everyone. And that’s the kind of result we were hoping for when we started.

BLOCKCHAIN FOR CARBON TRADING Author: - Digvijay Bangale, Pushpam Raj & Yashika Kumari Instructor: - Prof. Anil Vithalrao Turukmane  Abstract When we kicked off this project, our main thought was pretty simple: could blockchain actually make carbon trading better, or would it just be another flashy tech idea that sounds good on paper? We’d read about how credits get double counted, how deals take forever to verify, and how middlemen can swallow a big share of the money. It felt broken. We decided to try a different path — using ERC-20 tokens, smart contracts, and IoT devices so credits could be created, verified, and retired in a way that was transparent and quick. No unnecessary steps, no endless waiting. When we tested it, the difference was huge: settlement times dropped from days to minutes, costs went down to about 1–2%, and every step was visible to everyone involved. Honestly, it was satisfying to see something so simple make such a noticeable improvement.  Introduction One of the first things we talked about as a team was whether blockchain could solve real- world problems, not just sit there as a buzzword. Carbon markets have been around for a long time, but they aren’t smooth — you’ve got slow verification, high fees, and credits you can’t always trust. We wanted to build something that could work for both ends of the spectrum: a big company offsetting millions of tonnes and a small community planting trees by hand. The voluntary carbon market (VCM) is getting bigger every year — USD 4.04 billion in 2024, heading toward nearly USD 24 billion by 2030. That’s great, but if trust isn’t there, the growth could collapse in on itself. Our idea was to blend Ethereum-compatible smart contracts with real-time IoT monitoring. The blockchain side would handle the rules and transactions automatically, and the sensors would feed in live, verifiable environmental data. That’s how we aimed to plug the trust gap.  Background and Framework Carbon trading officially started with the Kyoto Protocol, then expanded through things like the EU Emissions Trading Scheme. The theory is good: measure emissions cuts, turn them into credits, trade them. But reality often means delays, paperwork, and costs that eat away at value. Some blockchain projects, like KlimaDAO and Toucan Protocol, have tried tokenizing credits already. They proved it was possible, but there were still cracks — like data reliability and the need to keep all participants engaged and honest. We went with the idea of “programmable environmental assets.” In our system, each token has embedded details about the project, the amount of CO₂ reduced, and the verification process. We broke the market into four main roles:  Consumers – buying credits (35%)  Generators – producing verified reductions (30%)  Validators – confirming authenticity (20%)  Regulators – overseeing compliance (15%) Blockchain Carbon Trading Stakeholders  System Design We structured the platform into four layers, mostly so it would be modular and easier to scale: 1. Blockchain Layer –

where tokens are created, traded, and eventually retired. 2. Application Layer – a Vue.js interface, so each type of user sees what’s relevant to them. 3. Integration Layer – connecting IoT sensors, satellite images, and registries. 4. User Layer – handling permissions and access control. When we compared it to the traditional process, the benefits were obvious: faster transactions, lower fees, no middlemen, real-time transparency, and the ability for anyone to take part from anywhere. Carbon Trading Comparison – Traditional vs Blockchain  Implementation and Results We set up the smart contracts on Hyperledger Fabric. It gave us over 1,000 transactions per second, credit issuance in around 2.3 seconds, and gas costs that were about 15–20% lower than a normal ERC-20 setup. It wasn’t all perfect. One rainy day, an IoT sensor went rogue and started sending odd CO₂ readings. The blockchain logged it without question, which reminded us — tech is only as good as the inputs. That’s why redundancy and validation layers are non-negotiable if this is going to work in the real world. Looking at where the carbon market is heading made us realise how big this could become. Carbon Market Growth Projections (2024–2030)  Feedback from Stakeholders We didn’t just want numbers — we wanted to hear from people. Most liked the transparency and the fact that once a credit was logged, it couldn’t be duplicated. Automated verification also made life easier by removing a lot of form-filling. Real-time monitoring gave buyers more confidence, which in turn could make the whole market more active. Key Benefits of Blockchain in Carbon Trading  Discussion One thing we learned quickly is that blockchain can improve speed and trust, but it’s not a magic wand. The real environmental value depends on accurate data, honest measurements, and solid governance. Without those, it’s just a fancy database. We also realised that cutting transaction costs could open the market to smaller projects. Before, many local or community-based initiatives couldn’t afford to join in. Now, they might be able to — and those smaller projects, when combined, could have a massive impact. There are still hurdles: smart contracts can be complex, rules vary by region, and there’s no universal standard for trading credits yet. But these are challenges we think can be solved with time and collaboration.  Conclusion We built something that worked in testing — it made trades faster, cheaper, and more transparent. But the takeaway isn’t that blockchain solves everything. It’s that, when combined with solid monitoring and good governance, it can be a real force for change. Next, we want to try it on live projects, strengthen our IoT setup so bad weather doesn’t throw it off, work with regulators to make sure everything is compliant, and explore ways for credits to move easily between platforms. If we can make that happen, the carbon market could become not just bigger, but better for everyone. And that’s the kind of result we were hoping for when we started.

Real-time monitoring gave buyers more confidence, which in turn could make the whole market more active. Key Benefits of Blockchain in Carbon Trading  Discussion One thing we learned quickly is that blockchain can improve speed and trust, but it’s not a magic wand. The real environmental value depends on accurate data, honest measurements, and solid governance. Without those, it’s just a fancy database. We also realised that cutting transaction costs could open the market to smaller projects. Before, many local or community-based initiatives couldn’t afford to join in. Now, they might be able to — and those smaller projects, when combined, could have a massive impact. There are still hurdles: smart contracts can be complex, rules vary by region, and there’s no universal standard for trading credits yet. But these are challenges we think can be solved with time and collaboration.  Conclusion We built something that worked in testing — it made trades faster, cheaper, and more transparent. But the takeaway isn’t that blockchain solves everything. It’s that, when combined with solid monitoring and good governance, it can be a real force for change. Next, we want to try it on live projects, strengthen our IoT setup so bad weather doesn’t throw it off, work with regulators to make sure everything is compliant, and explore ways for credits to move easily between platforms. If we can make that happen, the carbon market could become not just bigger, but better for everyone. And that’s the kind of result we were hoping for when we started.

Computer Science Concepts Introduction to Computer Science Computer Science is the study of algorithms, data structures, and the principles that underlie modern computing. It combines theoretical and practical aspects of computing. Key Fields in Computer Science: 1. Data Structures and Algorithms - The backbone of problem-solving in programming. 2. Computer Networks - The exchange of data between systems via protocols like TCP/IP. 3. Databases - Organized systems to manage, store, and retrieve information efficiently. 4. Artificial Intelligence - Enabling machines to learn and make decisions autonomously. 5. Cybersecurity - Protecting networks, systems, and data from malicious attacks. 6. Operating Systems - Software that manages hardware resources and provides services to applications. 7. Software Engineering - The process of designing, developing, testing, and maintaining reliable software. Applications of Computer Science: Computer Science has revolutionized industries — from AI in healthcare to automation in manufacturing, data analytics in finance, and cybersecurity in defense systems. Conclusion: With rapid advancements in AI, quantum computing, and data science, the field of Computer Science continues to expand, shaping the future of innovation and technology.
